A plot of the Brent formation pressure points can be seen in Fig.4.18. The FMT’s used for this plot are numbers 1,3,4,5. FMT’s number 16 and 17 were taken after the Statfjord points and may suffer slightly from lack of temperature stabilisation or hysteresis. The plot gives a water gradient of .097 bar/m. A.15 bar separation exists in the aquifer between the 25/5-2 and 25/2-14 wells. This demonstrates that the C- compartment is pressure separated from Fry in the Brent sequence. The formation pressure FMT’s from the Statfjord are plotted in Fig.4.19. FMT numbers 7,8,10,11,14 were used in this plot. The other points are apparently supercharged. These points show a water gradient for the Statfjord of .094 bar/m. The Statfjord in well 25/2-14 is obviously not in pressure communication with the Statfjord in well 25/5-1, The final FMT plot (Fig.4.20) for this well shows all the formation points taken in this well. The water bearing Brent formation is not in communication with the water bearing Statfjord formation in the well, however, it can not be excluded that there is pressure communication between the Brent sequence of 25/2-14 and the Statfjord formation below Froy. The primary target of well 35/3-5 was sandstones of Lower Cretaceous age which have been found hydrocarbon bearing in the 35/3-2 and 4 wells. The correlation between sandbodies have proved uncertain in the area due to complicated tectonic and sedimentological pattern. For that reason the well was considered as a wildcat. A secondary target was sandstones of Middle-Lower Jurassic age, which previously have been found to be hydrocarbon bearing (35/3-2), but with very poor reservoir characteristics. One set of canned samples was collected at 20 m composite interval from 410-1400 mRKB, at 10 m composite interval from 1400 mRKB to 2800 mRKB, and 9 m intervals from 2800 mRKB to T.D. Diestian - Middle Miocene 264 - 544 m (th. 280 ) ® Clay, soft, light-greenish grey, silty-sandy and micaceous, with lignite flakes is the main lithology of this unit. Some thin shaly sands occur towards the base of this unit they are very fine to medium grained and very glauconitic (442/444 m - 502/507 m and 541/544 m). Numerous glauconite pellets occur at the top of this unit and some red brown, sideritic, limestone stringers ure present above 650 m. These clays are dated Oligocene by their mannoflora content and are analogouc to the Cilleborg and Septarien clays of Denmark. Recent - Scaldisian 132 - 264 m (th 132). Sand and gravels with some light-grey very soft interbeds,and thick-shelled pelecypool debris. As the first returns were obtained at 445 m the lithologies to this depth are inferred from the Gamma-Ray curve and bit samples. 826 _-_984_m In this zone the clays are becoming more grey and admit more stringers of brown to buff sideritic micrites. (run No. 4) Note: There was no apparent pressure build-up when attempting to take a RFT sample and this was believed to be the result of formation sand/ calcium carbonate plugging the sampling probe. The RFT probe was, therefore, replaced by a larger one, but after numerous attempts, a PVT sample could still not be obtained. A hole depth of 1724 m was recorded and a subsequent check trip to bottom confirmed 9 metres of fill. The hole was washed/ reamed to 1735 m and circulated clean prior to running the 4th CST gun. After rigging down Schlumberger a check trip was made which found a hold-up depth at 1725 m. The hole was reamed to 1735 m and a further 9m of formation drilled to a new T.D of 1744 m, to allow an adequate pocket to run the 9-5/8" casing in the event of 9 m of infill. The 9-5/8" casing was run and cemented with shoe at 1720 m. The marine riser and BOP stack were pulled owing to a blockage in the kill line. When the stack was on surface it was observed that the kill line on the stack, and 5 joints of marine riser kill line were blocked with plugs of cement, rubber and metal from the cement plugs. The kill line was cleared and the failsafe valves on choke and kill lines were repaired. The stack was tested on surface and then run back on the marine riser and latched onto the wellhead. A full subsea stack test was then successfully carried out. Preparations were then made for production testing. The E-Z subsea test tree assembly was made up and spaced out on 43" PH-6 tubing riser. The flowhead was also made up. An 83" bit with tandem scrapers was run to tag the float collar and scrape the casing clean.
